e.Nicole Guenther Discenza looks at the sources Alfred used in his translation and demonstrates his selectivity in choosing what to retain, what to borrow, and how to represent it to his Anglo-Saxon audience. Alfred's appeals to Latin prestige, spiritual authority, Old English poetry, and everyday experience in England combine to make the Old English Boethius a powerful text and a rich source for our understanding of Anglo-Saxon literature, culture, and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEnglish languageyOld English, ca. 450-1100xStyle. 0aLatin languagexTranslating into EnglishxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aTranslating and interpretingzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Medieval Studies. 4aLiterature : English Literature. 4aLiterature : Translation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483237/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles